HQ elements usually held Reserve; being a 4hth PLT would make sense, as a maneuver Tank Company was usually 3 Tank platoons), *  Headquarters Company ( HHC today)* 533rd Tank Batallion * 84th Infantry Division ( Divisional Armored support ) They would have likely supported an INF RGT as they were not organic to the 84th ID. The 84th INF Division was a REserve DIV that landed in /France in Nov 1944 and fought there and in Germany through 1945.A very interesting holster to trace and research.  $299 + 15 shipp.Feel free to EM or call with questions.

title: For Sale:  Stevens Model 200 20 gauge pump shotgun
postcontent:
Stevens Model 200 20 gauge pump shotgun. Here is a rare one for the Stevens collector. The last patent date is 1912. I purchased this gun from a Stevens collector years ago.  Shot wobble trap with it once, using Winchester Super Target 2 3/4" 7/8oz. #8 Shot, and the gun performed flawlessly.  Then cleaned the gun and stored it in my safe ever since.  Gun comes with a file of information including patent drawings, a component parts list, and a 1968 "Guns & Amo" magazine with an artice about the Model 200.  This gun also includes the spanner, which is a part often missing from Model 200s these days. 
The Stevens Model 200, 20 gauge pump shotgun was the first manufactured 20 Gauge Pump Shotgun. It was the brainchild of the famous trap shooter, Charles (Sparrow) Young. Sparrow Young is in the trapshooting hall of fame and was the first shooter to break 100 straight from back yardage. In 1910 he patented the original idea which became the Model 200.  The Stevens Model 200 was only made from about 1911 to 1914. The gun was meant to be a combination of a light "field" type gun for upland game with a heavy duck gun (when firing 3" shells).
The Stevens Model 200 was considered the King of The Turkey Shoot Circuit in the 1920's. This is a 5-shot gun that weighs about 6.5 lbs.  Note that the stock was well-repaired by a previous owner (see pics). Additional pics available upon request.
For FTF sale in VA, buyer must be 18+ years of age and have a VA driver’s license.  For an out-of-state sale, will arrange shipment to buyer’s FFL, at buyer’s cost.
Transaction will include bill of sale. Sorry, no trades at this time. Still available if posted.

title: For Sale:  You all are awful, disgusting people
postcontent: I have been buying/selling/trading guns on here for about 5 years. Within the past year or so the kind of people that have come onto this site are just awful fucking excuses of human beings. When I post something for sale, which is posted at a very fair price, and you come email me and just say "what is your lowest price?", I want to rip your teeth out. That is a terribly insulting question. When I post an item for sale, the price I have posted is a very fair and equitable price, that includes a little wiggle room for negotiation. I AM willing to go lower than my asking price. But, if and when I respond to your cringeworthy question about my lowest price and then you try to drive the price down even further?!?!? Fuck off! If you are interested in my item, and feel the price I am asking is too high, email me an offer. When you do, one of three things will happen; I will accept your offer because you are not trying to be a low balling asshole and the price you are offering is within my range of acceptable offers, I will flat out reject your offer if you are so absurdly below my asking price that I feel there is too big of a gap to find an agreeable number, or, I will counter your offer if it is maybe a hair below what I would be willing to accept and I try to get to my minimum asking price, and if you do not come up on your offer, I will likely choose to accept it and eat a little more loss than I would've hoped for, and then you get a great deal on an item and everyone walks away happy. It angers me to no end when I post something and then start getting offers for 1/3-1/2 below my asking price. The point of this site is that when people try to sell something used, they are trying to get a slightly higher price than what their local gun shop will offer them. And when you're in the market for a used item, you can generally find it priced lower than your local gun store is selling it for. But when a private buyer makes offers that are equal to and in MANY cases lower than what a gun shop offers that has to pay for their physical store and employee costs, then you are just awful fucking people destroying the intent of this site

title: For Sale:  Chiefs Special Smith & Wesson Flat Latch Snubnose Revolver circa 1956
postcontent: Local face-to-face cash sale only. Buyer must be at least 21, Oklahoma resident able to legally buy a firearm in Oklahoma, and must have a current valid Oklahoma issued picture ID. No exceptions.Some of the hardest guns for me to sell as I consolidate down to just a couple are the ones that would be so difficult to replace. That is the case with the oldest model of a Smith & Wesson Chiefs Special that I have owned. It is a pre-Model 36 version J-frame built in 1956. That's right...this classic snubnose revolver is sixty years old but you couldn't tell it by looking at or shooting it. Designed to be small and compact for easy carry conceal or small storage areas, this pre-Model 36 Flat Latch J-frame Chiefs Special has a pinned 1.875 inch (sometimes called a 2 inch) barrel. It has 5-round capacity in a swing-out cylinder and can be fired in single or double action.This gun has a grooved rear sight and a ramped fixed blade front sight. It features a blued finish and has the original diamond-type wood grips with serial numbers that match the round butt frame.This classic S&W revolver is in great condition for its age. There is some honest holster wear on the bottom front of the frame and muzzle and a small chip in the bottom of the upper portion of the right wood grip. This gun was carried some but only occasionally fired. Very clean and shiny bore and cylinders with no rust or damage on this gun. I had the gun's side plate off and completely cleaned while intact the internals, then oiled them before replacing the side plate. That helped improve an already smooth trigger and added to the accuracy of the gun.I have fired 50 problem-free rounds of factory .38 Special 130 grain factory ammunition through it since I acquired it. As with all of the S&W revolvers I have had the pleasure to shoot, this one is fun and confidence-inspiring. This revolver is one that is of the age it could be put away in a collection to fondle and admire, but is also dependable and accurate enough to carry conceal or use as a house gun. Comes safely nested inside a new Bore Stores Silicone Treated Gun Storage rug.Please contact me for several additional pictures.

title: For Sale:  Stevens Model 200 20 gauge pump shotgun
postcontent:
Stevens Model 200 20 gauge pump shotgun. Here is a rare one for the shotgun collector. The Model 200 was manufactured from 1911 to 1914, with only 20,000 produced.  Serial no. 189XX.
The last patent date is 1912. I purchased this gun from a Stevens collector years ago.  Shot trap with it once, using Winchester Super Target 2 3/4" 7/8oz. #8 Shot, and the gun performed flawlessly.  Then cleaned the gun and stored it in my safe ever since.  Gun comes with a file of information including patent drawings, a component parts list, and a 1968 "Guns & Ammo" magazine with an article about the Model 200.  This gun also includes the spanner, which is a part often missing from Model 200s these days. 
The Stevens Model 200, 20 gauge pump shotgun was the first manufactured 20 Gauge Pump Shotgun. It was the brainchild of the famous trap shooter, Charles (Sparrow) Young. Sparrow Young is in the trapshooting hall of fame and was the first shooter to break 100 straight from back yardage. In 1910 he patented the original idea which became the Model 200.  The gun was meant to be a combination of a light "field" type gun for upland game with a heavy duck gun (when firing 3" shells).
 
The Stevens Model 200 was considered the King of The Turkey Shoot Circuit in the 1920's. This is a 5-shot gun that weighs about 6.5 lbs.  Note that the stock was well-repaired by a previous owner (see pics). Additional pics available upon request.
 
For FTF sale in VA, buyer must be 18+ years of age and have a VA driver’s license.  For an out-of-state sale, will arrange shipment to buyer’s FFL, at buyer’s cost.
Asking $800.  Open to reasonable offers / trades.
Transaction will include bill of sale. Still available if posted.  Thanks for looking!
